com.infinitydb.map.lambda

Class CollectingThreadedMapVisitor<K,V,R,T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.infinitydb.map.visitor.MapVisitor<K,V>
      • com.infinitydb.map.visitor.ThreadedMapVisitor<K,V>
        • com.infinitydb.map.lambda.CollectingThreadedMapVisitor<K,V,R,T>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - key
    V - value
    R - result of the entire operation returned by getResult()
    T - temporary internal result of mapper, input to accumulator.

    public class CollectingThreadedMapVisitor<K,V,R,T>
extends ThreadedMapVisitor<K,V>
    A ThreadedMapVisitor that works like: 
     result = map.stream().parallel().map(mapper).collect(supplier, accumulator, combiner);
    but often with higher performance. It falls back to actual parallel streams if necessary. Because it uses features of Java 8, it is not backwards compatible. The same functionality can be achieved portably and with higher performance without Java 8 features by extending MapVisitor or ThreadedMapVisitor and passing that to a Visitable such as a VisitableMap like AirConcurrentMap or others. Others can include various Visitable wrappers like VisitableArrayWrapper, VisitableSetWrapper, or VisitableListWrapper. For example: 
     result = new CollectingThreadedMapVisitor(
              mapper, supplier, accumulator, combiner).getResult(map);
    The performance improvement is about 3 to 7 times.
    See Also:
    ThreadedMapVisitor, MapVisitor, Visitable, VisitableMap

    • Method Detail

      • getResult

        public R getResult(java.util.Map<K,V> map)
        This makes AirConcurrentMap use its internal threading for even more speed than Java 8 parallel streams - about 3 to 7 times faster, and for Java 6 and 7, it is 10 to 20 times faster than Iterators. Even if the Map supplied is not capable of threading but only visiting, it will use visiting, which is a few times faster than Iterators in Java 6/7.
        Parameters:
        map - the Map to scan over and do the collecting
        Returns:
        the collection into which the scan puts the collected Objects of type T.

      • visit

        public void visit(K key,
                  V value)
        Description copied from class: MapVisitor
        Called once per Entry in the Map. No other methods need to be overridden as they all delegate to this one. It is convenient to implement a very general-purpose method here, and then override the others as desired if that will increase speed. There is no other flavor - it is not different for keys, entries, or values. Thus there is no need for Map.keySet(), Map.entrySet() and Map.values() etc.
        Specified by:
        visit in class MapVisitor<K,V>
        Parameters:
        key - the key in a given Entry at a point int the scan.
        value - corresponds to the single unique key

      • split

        public CollectingThreadedMapVisitor<K,V,R,T> split()
        Description copied from class: ThreadedMapVisitor
        Create a new Visitor from this one. This may require transferring some state from the current one to the new one. Visitors may be split during the work of the threads in the thread pool for the Map. Eventually, all of the split-off Visitors are merged together. This is not called by multiple threads at once. There is no guarantee that the VisitableMap will invoke this at all, and it may choose to do the splitting in any way it chooses. The new ThreadedMapVisitor may be used by a different thread than the one that invokes split.
        Specified by:
        split in class ThreadedMapVisitor<K,V>
        Returns:
        A new ThreadedMapVisitor for the threaded visitation to use in a new thread until it is merged back to the original.

      • merge

        public void merge(ThreadedMapVisitor<K,V> otherVisitor)
        Description copied from class: ThreadedMapVisitor
        Merge two visitors together. Only one thread will call this at a time. The original Visitor, provided to the VisitableMap, will eventually be merged with all of the ones that have been split off. The merges are not guaranteed to happen in any pattern, so the threads are free to do splits and merges in any way desired.
        Specified by:
        merge in class ThreadedMapVisitor<K,V>
        Parameters:
        otherVisitor - the source of the state to be merged into this visitor.
